**Abstract:**
A philosophical essay dated April 23, 1996 on "Fideism and Skepticism" arguing that if the Enlightenment's standard of rationality were valid, both faith and science would be fideistic. Monasterio traces the Greek misconception of the epistemic subject as a "purely curious, invulnerable contemplator" and proposes the alternative of the "involved vulnerable agent." Discusses how post-modernism remains bound to this Greek model, leading to generalized skepticism.

**AI Recommendation:** Major essay developing Monasterio's critique of traditional epistemology and its implications for faith.

